{{italic title}} '''''Finn's Hotel''''' is a posthumously-published collection of ten short narrative pieces written by Irish author [[James Joyce]].<ref name="guardian">[https://www.theguardian.com/books/2013/jun/14/james-joyce-collection-published James Joyce's 'last undiscovered' collection to be published | Books | theguardian.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Written in 1923, the works were not published until 2013 by [[Ithys Press]], who claimed the work to be a precursor to Joyce's ''[[Finnegans Wake]]''.<ref name=ithyspress>[http://ithyspress.wordpress.com/2013/06/14/finns-hotel-by-james-joyce-first-edition-just-published/ "''Finn's Hotel'' by James Joyce"], ''Ithys Press''</ref>
==Publication== Ithys Press published their fine arts edition of ''Finn's Hotel'' in June 2013.<ref name=ithyspress /> The edition was arranged with a preface by Danis Rose, an introduction by [[Seamus Deane]], featuring eleven illustrations by [[Casey Sorrow]], and design and letterpress printed by Michael Caine.
The publication attracted controversy as some Joyce scholars labeled the works as drafts, not meant for publication.<ref name="guardian" /><ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/books/00/01/09/specials/joyce-lost.html A Lost Work by Joyce Fuels Scholarly Debate<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[http://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2013/06/ithys-press-to-release-10-lost-james-joyce-works.html Ithys Press to Release 10 Lost James Joyce Works as Finn's Hotel :: Books :: News :: Paste<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[http://www.bbook.com/literature-nerds-freaking-out-about-lost-james-joyce-collection/ Literature Nerds Freaking Out About ‘Lost’ James Joyce Collection | BlackBook<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>
In the spring of 2014, James O'Sullivan wrote an article for Genetic Joyce Studies, “Finn’s Hotel and the Joycean Canon”, which uses computational stylistics to analyze the text of ''Finn's Hotel'' to determine whether the text is merely early drafts or should be part of Joyce's canon. O'Sullivan concluded that "the fragments within ''Finn’s Hotel'' are most likely drafts for what became ''Finnegans Wake''" and that statistically "the criticisms of Ithys Press are seemingly upheld."<ref>{{cite web|last1=O'Sullivan|first1=James|title=Using stylometry to weigh in on the Finn’s Hotel debate|url=http://josullivan.org/using-stylometry-to-weigh-in-on-the-finns-hotel-debate/|website=http://josullivan.org/}}</ref>
