The '''"first possession" theory of property''' holds that ownership of something is justified simply by someone seizing it before someone else does.<ref>"Property". Graham Oppy. ''The shorter Routledge encyclopedia of philosophy''. Editor [[Edward Craig (philosopher)|Edward Craig]]. Routledge, 2005, p. 858</ref> This contrasts with the [[labor theory of property]] where something may become property only by applying productive labor to it, i.e. by making something out of the materials of nature.

